<h2 id="GuidComm">1. Guiding commitments</h2>

<h3 id="UnivInte">1.1 Universal intelligibility</h3>

<p>
One of Spinoza&rsquo;s most fundamental epistemological and
methodological commitments is a commitment to universal
intelligibility. In his most influential treatise, the
<em>Ethics</em>, Spinoza expresses this commitment in two ways: first,
as the axiom that there is nothing that cannot be
&ldquo;conceived&rdquo;, either &ldquo;through itself&rdquo; or
through &ldquo;another thing&rdquo; (<em>Ethics</em> [=
<strong>E</strong>] 1ax2); second, as the claim that there is a
&ldquo;reason <em>or</em> [i.e.] cause&rdquo; for the &ldquo;existence
or nonexistence&rdquo; of every thing (E1p11atld1).</p>

<p>
These formulations immediately raise several questions. What does it
mean for something to be conceived &ldquo;through itself&rdquo;, i.e.,
in some sense be <em>self</em>-explanatory? Does the equivalence of
causes and reasons suggested by E1p11altd1 mean that only appeals to
<em>causes</em> can furnish reasons? Indeed, what counts as a
&ldquo;reason&rdquo; (cf. Lin 2018)? It&rsquo;s often assumed that in
Spinoza&rsquo;s view to give a &ldquo;reason&rdquo; for something
requires engaging in the sort of apriori deductions that fill large
swathes of the <em>Ethics</em>. The opening definition of the
treatise, according to which something is a &ldquo;cause of
itself&rdquo; if its existence is implied by its essence (E1def1),
suggests that at least some of the relevant &ldquo;reasons&rdquo; will
indeed be accessible apriori. But could sense experience also furnish
us with reasons? Is seeing my dog play with a stick enough of a
&ldquo;reason&rdquo; to &ldquo;conceive&rdquo; of her as existing, or
must I deduce her necessary existence from the infinitely long series
of prior causes (E1p28), a task Spinoza admits is impossible for
finite minds like ours (<em>Treatise on the Emendation of the
Intellect</em> [= <strong>TIE</strong>] &sect;100)?</p>

<p>
Controversially but influentially, Michael Della Rocca 2008 has argued
that Spinoza&rsquo;s philosophy as a whole can be derived from his
commitment to intelligibility. (For criticisms see e.g. Laerke 2011,
Newlands 2018, Renz 2018.)</p>

<h3 id="AttrBarr">1.2 Attribute barrier</h3>

<p>
A second guiding but unintuitive commitment of Spinoza&rsquo;s
epistemology has come to be known as the &ldquo;attribute
barrier&rdquo;. A Spinozistic &ldquo;attribute&rdquo; is a descendant
of the Cartesian &ldquo;principal attribute&rdquo; (AT 8a.25):
roughly, it is the most basic qualitative kind under which something
can fall. For example, to say that something is a mental thing or a
physical thing &ndash; or, in Spinoza&rsquo;s and Descartes&rsquo;s
terminology, &ldquo;thinking&rdquo; or &ldquo;extended&rdquo; &ndash;
is to understand it in terms of its particular
&ldquo;attribute&rdquo;.</p>

<p>
Most commentators take Spinoza to uphold a total explanatory
<em>closure</em> of mental and physical realms: pace Descartes, no
physical thing can enter into conceptual or explanatory relations with
anything mental, and vice versa. For example, regardless of how we
might experience things, no physical occurrence, such as shaking a
fist at someone, can be made intelligible by appealing to anything
mental, like a menacing intention. Analogously, no bodily injury can
make intelligible the feeling of pain.</p>

<p>
This prohibition on any &ldquo;explanatory flow&rdquo; (Bennett 1984)
between mental and physical realms is the core meaning of
Spinoza&rsquo;s attribute barrier doctrine. Given Spinoza&rsquo;s
commitment to universal intelligibility (see 1.1), derivatively, the
impossibility of conceptual relations between minds and bodies implies
the impossibility of <em>causal</em> relations between them (E3p2s).
For if something is in principle unintelligible (as any purported
causal relation between minds and bodies would be), it is also
metaphysically impossible. This prohibition on causal interactions
between mental and physical things is the key secondary meaning of the
barrier doctrine.</p>

<p>
Given that ordinarily we <em>do</em> appeal to intentions in
explaining our physical actions and to bodily states in explaining
sensations, what would lead Spinoza to such a prima facie implausible
doctrine? The reason ultimately has to do with how Spinoza understands
the nature of the most fundamental entity in his metaphysics,
&ldquo;substance&rdquo;. Building on philosophical tradition that goes
back to Aristotle, Spinoza associates being a &ldquo;substance&rdquo;
with existential and explanatory self-sufficiency or independence
(E1def3). Each essential quality or &ldquo;attribute&rdquo; of
substance also must, Spinoza believes, manifest this independence
proper to substance: &ldquo;Each attribute of a substance must be
conceived through itself&rdquo; (E1p10). As a result, we cannot look
for an explanation of the fact that substance thinks, or of how it
thinks, anywhere else but in substance&rsquo;s thinking nature (for
example, we cannot appeal to the fact that it is also a material
thing, i.e., a substance with the attribute of
&ldquo;extension&rdquo;). In this sense substance as thinking is
&ldquo;conceived through itself&rdquo;. The same reasoning will be
true of any other substantial attribute.</p>

<p>
This gives us the basic application of the barrier doctrine: the fact
that God is a physical thing cannot explain God&rsquo;s nature as a
thinking thing; nor is explanation possible in the other direction.
But the barrier doctrine also extends to <em>creaturely</em>
intentions, sensations, and movements. Ontologically, all the things
familiar to us from ordinary experience &ndash; animals, plants,
inanimate objects &ndash; are for Spinoza merely modifications or
&ldquo;modes&rdquo; of the single substance, &ldquo;ways
[<em>modis</em>]&rdquo; that God is, just as (to borrow examples from
Lin 2018) a wrinkle in a rug is one way a rug can be, and a fist one
way a hand can be. Spinoza explicitly applies the barrier doctrine
also to modes, stating that no modification of the thinking substance
can require for its explanation the concept <em>extension</em>, and no
modification of the extended substance can require for its explanation
the concept <em>thought</em>:</p>

<blockquote>
each attribute is conceived through itself without any other (by
1p10). So the modes of each attribute involve the concept of their own
attribute, but not of another one. (E2p6d)
</blockquote>

<p>
(On attributes, see e.g. Gueroult 1968, Deleuze 1968, Shein 2009, Lin
2019.)</p>

<h3 id="PrioInfiThin">1.3 The priority of an infinite thinker</h3>

<p>
As we just saw, Spinoza derives his prohibition of mental explanations
of physical actions from what he takes to be true of the relation
between the mental and the physical in the case of <em>God.</em> This
is an instance of a more general methodological and epistemological
principle Spinoza holds dear, that of the <em>explanatory
priority</em> of claims about substance (God) to claims about modes
(creatures) (E1p1, E1p15). To return to our toy analogy, we can only
understand what it is to be a wrinkle in a rug if we first understand
what it is to be a rug. For Spinoza, philosophizing in proper order
always requires us to start with substance (E2p10s).</p>

<p>
Given this explanatory priority of substance, to understand what it
means to <em>think</em> or to have a <em>mind</em>, we also cannot
simply extrapolate from <em>our</em> own case (for example, from
introspection, or from observing the behavior of fellow humans).
Rather, to understand thought and mindedness we first have to
understand the nature of <em>substantial</em> thought, i.e., what it
means to be an &ldquo;infinite&rdquo; &ndash; unlimited and
self-sufficient &ndash; thinker. This is the fundamental case of
thinking for Spinoza.</p>

<p>
What does this infinite thought amount to? In one sense, Spinoza is
simply endorsing here the traditional doctrine of divine omniscience.
In Spinoza&rsquo;s framework, this doctrine becomes the claim that, as
a thinking thing (i.e., a substance with the &ldquo;attribute&rdquo;
of thought) God necessarily <em>produces</em> an &ldquo;infinite
idea&rdquo;, that is, an infinite modification of God&rsquo;s nature
as a thinking thing (E2p1, E2p3, E2p7c). This infinite <em>idea
Dei</em> is a complete and veridical representation of everything that
is, every bit of reality (E2p32). (Spinoza also posits another
infinite mode in thought, an &ldquo;infinite intellect&rdquo; [e.g.,
E2p11c], which many readers take to be just another name for the
infinite <em>idea Dei</em>.)</p>

<p>
It&rsquo;s worth keeping in mind that Spinoza is making two distinct
claims here: to say that God is a substance with the attribute of
thought (that is, a thing whose essential nature it is to think) is
ontologically and explanatorily <em>prior</em> to the claim that this
thinking substance also <em>produces</em> an actual representation or
idea of everything (which is a claim about the existence of a certain
infinite <em>mode</em>). So although Spinoza faithfully follows
theological tradition in endorsing the claims that God thinks and is
omniscient, he also ends up with a quite nontraditional result: the
divine &ldquo;infinite intellect&rdquo; is not part of, or identical
with, divine <em>nature</em> <em>or essence</em>. In terms of its
ontological status, the divine intellect is on par with finite
&ldquo;minds&rdquo; insofar as these too are merely modes.</p>

<p>
The belief that the metaphysically basic instance of thinking consists
in the thinking done by an infallible and omniscient thinker goes some
way toward explaining why Spinoza seems unconcerned about the threat
of skepticism, so salient for Descartes (see also 3.1). For Spinoza
thought in its fundamental instance is necessarily true; that is, it
&ldquo;agrees&rdquo; (E1ax6) with how things really are. So
<em>global</em> skepticism is simply a metaphysical impossibility; all
that remains of the skeptical threat is to be on guard against local
instances of confusion and error that become possible in the
derivative case of finite thought. Moreover, all such confusion and
error need some further cause beyond the intrinsic nature of thought.
(Indeed, one might worry that Spinoza lets the pendulum swing too far
in the opposite direction: global skepticism might no longer be
possible, but it might now be hard to see how <em>error</em> could be
possible, if, in Spinoza&rsquo;s substance-monistic framework, all
ideas are ultimately God&rsquo;s own [see 3.2.2].)</p>

<p>
(On Spinoza&rsquo;s understanding of thinking, see e.g. Melamed 2013,
Newlands 2018, Renz 2018; on his two proofs that God thinks, e.g.
Bennett 1984, Della Rocca 1996, Gueroult 1974; on skepticism, e.g.
Carriero 2020, Perler 2018, Primus 2017.)</p>

<h3 id="PhilWayLife">1.4 Philosophy as a way of life</h3>

<p>
Last but not least, we should not forget that Spinoza&rsquo;s magnum
opus carries the title <em>Ethics.</em> For him knowledge is not
merely a <em>theoretical</em> achievement, as if we were solving
conceptual puzzles for their own sake. For Spinoza, what is at stake
in understanding anything, including the nature of thinking and
knowledge, is a whole slew of <em>practical</em> goods: freedom,
virtue, blessedness. Of the infinity of knowable things, Spinoza
writes, he wants to write only about &ldquo;those that can lead us, by
the hand, as it were, to the knowledge of the human Mind and its
highest blessedness&rdquo; (E2pref).</p>

<h2 id="PhilMind">2. Philosophy of mind</h2>

<h3 id="Mind">2.1 Minds</h3>

<h4 id="MindBund">2.1.1 Minds as bundles</h4>

<p>
One reason why Spinoza might not care about distinguishing between
calling something God&rsquo;s &ldquo;idea&rdquo; and calling it
God&rsquo;s &ldquo;intellect&rdquo; (see 1.3) is that, like Hume, he
appears to endorse what we today would call the &ldquo;bundle
theory&rdquo; of mind. On this theory, there is nothing more to
&ldquo;minds&rdquo; and &ldquo;intellects&rdquo; than collections of
ideas of various complexity. (For example, the &ldquo;idea that
constitutes the formal being of the human mind is&hellip;composed of a
great many ideas&rdquo; [E2p15].) In particular, minds do not contain
any specialized &ldquo;faculties&rdquo;, such as will or intellect
(E2p48). If notions of such faculties are to have any validity at all,
they must be understood as mere <em>abstractions</em> from particular
ideas and particular volitions (E2p48s; G/II/130).</p>

<p>
For Spinoza, what <em>individuates</em> one bundle of ideas from
another seem to be their intentional objects, i.e., what they
represent (E2p13s; see 2.1.3&ndash;4). For example, the aforementioned
highly composite idea that is the &ldquo;human mind&rdquo; has a
certain &ldquo;actually existing body&rdquo; as its essential object
(see 2.2).</p>

<p>
(On Spinoza&rsquo;s bundle-theoretic view of the mind, see e.g. Della
Rocca 1996; H&uuml;bner 2019; Renz 2018. On abstraction, see 3.2.4; on
the relation between ideas and affirmations, see 2.4; on the human
mind specifically see 2.2.)</p>

<h4 id="MindPart">2.1.2 Minds as parts</h4>

<p>
Spinoza&rsquo;s ground-floor commitment to substance monism (i.e., to
the metaphysical possibility of only one &ldquo;substance&rdquo;,
i.e., one existentially and explanatorily independent thing [E1def3])
leaves him with the problem of how to account for <em>finite</em>
thought. If only one, infinite substance exists, how should we
understand the ontological status of human minds? These cannot be
thinking <em>substances</em> (as they are, say, for Descartes or
Leibniz). Short of condemning all finite thinking as illusory, Spinoza
seems to have only one option left: to identify certain instances of
<em>substance</em>&rsquo;<em>s</em> thoughts with finite thinking. And this is
exactly what Spinoza does: he proposes that we regard all finite
ideas, and all the finite &ldquo;minds&rdquo; that these ideas compose
(see 2.1.1), as &ldquo;parts&rdquo; of the divine &ldquo;infinite
intellect&rdquo;:</p>

<blockquote>
the human mind is a part [<em>pars</em>] of the infinite intellect of
God. Therefore, when we say that the human mind perceives this or
that, we are saying nothing but that God, not insofar as he is
infinite, but insofar as he is explained through the nature of the
human mind, or insofar as he constitutes the essence of the human
mind, has this or that idea. (E2p11c)
</blockquote>

<p>
Finite minds are thus for Spinoza both <em>modes</em> of a thinking
<em>substance</em> and <em>parts</em> of an <em>infinite</em>
<em>mode</em> that is God&rsquo;s own &ldquo;intellect&rdquo;.</p>

<p>
The claim that finite minds are parts of the divine intellect may
answer the question of the ontological status of finite thought, but
it creates another puzzle: in what sense can a non-extended mind or
intellect be a &ldquo;part&rdquo;, or have &ldquo;parts&rdquo;,
moreover parts that are themselves &ldquo;minds&rdquo;? How would
Spinoza respond to the objection that we experienced our own
mindedness as indivisible? And what principle of division is proper to
non-spatial things?</p>

<h4 id="Panp">2.1.3 Panpsychism</h4>

<p>
As we just saw, Spinoza accommodates human minds within his
substance-monistic framework by carving up God&rsquo;s &ldquo;infinite
intellect&rdquo; into &ldquo;parts&rdquo;. But he isn&rsquo;t
concerned solely with making room in his metaphysics for
<em>human</em> minds:</p>

<blockquote>
the things we have shown so far are completely general and do not
pertain more to man than to other individuals, all of which, though in
different degrees, are nevertheless animate [<em>animata</em>]. For of
each thing there is necessarily an idea in God, of which God is the
cause in the same way as he is of the [human mind] (E2p13s)
</blockquote>

<p>
This is Spinoza&rsquo;s thesis of panpsychism, or universal mindedness
(more precisely, universal at least for all &ldquo;individuals&rdquo;
or composite entities [E2def; G/II/100]). Panpsychism follows because
all it takes for there to be a finite &ldquo;mind&rdquo; in
Spinoza&rsquo;s view is that there be some &ldquo;part&rdquo; of the
omniscient divine intellect &ndash; some component idea of it &ndash;
that represents some discernible bit of being. So not only is there
nothing more to minds than ideas (2.1.1), there is nothing more to
creaturely minds than God&rsquo;s ideas.</p>

<p>
Spinoza&rsquo;s panpsychism certainly seems more <em>morally</em>
appealing than the vivisection-friendly Cartesian view that animals
are just more complex versions of tables and clocks. Yet one may also
wonder whether an account that can explain how <em>human</em>
mindedness is possible only by instituting a general principle &ndash;
namely, the divisibility of an omniscient infinite intellect into
component ideas &ndash; that ushers in also plant and mineral minds
has diluted the meaning of &ldquo;mind&rdquo; beyond recognition or
usefulness. Can an account that sees mindedness everywhere explain
phenomena that, to all appearances, are particular to <em>human</em>
rationality and self-consciousness? And is Spinoza not guilty here
simply of a profound confusion of categories: how can <em>my</em>
<em>mind</em> just be <em>another</em> subject&rsquo;s <em>idea</em> of
something? (Margaret Wilson expressed the classic version of these
worries, pessimistically judging against Spinoza [1999: ch.9].)</p>

<p>
(On Spinozistic minds, see e.g. Alanen 2011, Koistinen 2018, Lin 2017,
Newlands 2012; on mind-relativity of representing, see e.g. Matheron
1969, Donagan 1988, Della Rocca 1996; on individuation of subjects,
Renz 2018.)</p>

<h3 id="HumaMind">2.2 Human minds</h3>

<h4 id="IdeaBodi">2.2.1 Ideas of bodies</h4>

<p>
Any plausible panpsychism will have to say something about how human
minds differ from all other minds that populate reality. Spinoza
accounts for the distinctiveness of the human mind in two ways. First,
as already noted, he underscores its <em>complexity</em> as a mental
operation or act of thinking. Using the Scholastic term &ldquo;formal
being&rdquo; to pick out this aspect of thinking, he writes,
&ldquo;the idea that constitutes the formal being of the human mind
is&hellip;composed of a great many ideas&rdquo; (E2p15). Second,
Spinoza proposes that human minds are also distinct by virtue of what
they essentially <em>represent</em>: the essential intentional object
of the human mind is an <em>actually existing body</em>:</p>

<blockquote>

<p>
The object of the idea constituting the human mind is the body,
<em>or</em> a certain mode of Extension which actually exists, and
nothing else (E2p13)</p>

<p>
the essence of the mind consists in this&hellip;that it affirms the
actual existence of its body (E3GenDefAff [G/II/204]; cf. E2p11,
E2p17s [G/II/105/32])</p>
</blockquote>

<p>
In other words, a certain (itself complex) &ldquo;part&rdquo; of the
divine infinite intellect will count as a &ldquo;human mind&rdquo; iff
it essentially represents a certain physical existent. It is in this
intentional or representational relation (and not for example, <em>per
impossibile</em>, in some <em>causal</em> relation [see 1.2]) that the
mind-body &ldquo;union&rdquo; consists in Spinoza&rsquo;s view:
&ldquo;We have shown that the Mind is united to the Body from the fact
that the Body is the object of the Mind&rdquo; (E2p21d) (cf. Renz
2018).</p>

<p>
A few clarifications are in order. First, on hearing of
Spinoza&rsquo;s view, we might be inclined to protest that human minds
represent all sorts of things <em>other</em> than our own bodies:
other bodies, thoughts, abstract objects, etc. (cf. Wilson 1999: ch.
9). But, to be clear, Spinoza <em>isn&rsquo;t</em> proposing here,
implausibly, that we represent <em>nothing but</em> our own bodies.
His claim is rather about what &ldquo;constitutes&rdquo; the
<em>essential</em> intentional object of the human mind: other ideas
composing my mind may come and go, but to remain the same mind across
time, and distinct from other equally complex bundles of ideas, my
mind must continue to represent a particular physical entity.
Moreover, Spinoza holds that we are able to represent all the other
things we represent only because we first conceive of our own body.
For example, it is only by representing our own bodily changes that we
can represent the bodies that are their external causes (for example,
it is only through representing an itch that I can represent poison
ivy); likewise, it is only in virtue of representing the essence of
that body that we can represent things in their eternal being (E5p29).
(For details, see 3.2 and 4).</p>

<p>
Second, that my mind has some actually existing body for its essential
intentional object also <em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> mean that <em>I</em>
know this body <em>adequately</em>. Far from it: &ldquo;we have only
completely confused cognition of our body&rdquo; (E2p13s; cf. E2p27).
There are several reasons why Spinoza is led to this pessimistic
verdict. For one, as we just saw, the human mind is essentially an
idea of some existing body and of &ldquo;nothing else&rdquo; (E2p13).
In particular, the human mind is <em>not</em> essentially an idea of
the many <em>causes</em> responsible for that body&rsquo;s composition
and continued functioning. But, on Spinoza&rsquo;s conception of
knowledge, understanding these causes would be necessary for a
complete and so &ldquo;adequate&rdquo; knowledge of that body (E1ax4,
E2p11c; cf. Donagan 1988: 129). God, in knowing all these causes in
addition to having an idea of the body in question has in contrast a
perfectly adequate knowledge of it.</p>

<p>
Here is a second reason why, relative to what we can know, the idea
that is essential to our minds is &ldquo;completely confused&rdquo;.
According to Spinoza, the only way I can cognize my own body as a
particular thing existing in time (as opposed to knowing its atemporal
&ldquo;essence&rdquo;, or knowing the <em>general</em> properties of
all bodies) is through its modes or &ldquo;affections&rdquo; &ndash;
that is, through the changes or determinations that this body
undergoes, mostly under the influence of external causes (E2p19).
&ldquo;We feel that a certain body is affected in many ways&rdquo;
(E2ax4): we stub our toes, hear a voice, are warmed by the sun, etc.
But what we grasp in such first-personal experiences is, according to
Spinoza, only a &ldquo;confused&rdquo; <em>amalgam</em> of the nature
of our own body <em>and</em> the nature of the external causes
affecting it (for details, see 3.2.2).</p>

<p>
(See 4 for continuation of this account; on sense experience and
error, see 3.1.2, 3.2.3.)</p>

<h4 id="KnowYourPancOtheProb">2.2.2 Knowing your pancreas and other problems</h4>

<p>
Recognition that we have only &ldquo;completely confused&rdquo;
(E2p13s) cognition of the body whose ideas nonetheless essentially
&ldquo;constitutes&rdquo; a human mind is goes some way toward
defusing Spinoza&rsquo;s otherwise baffling assertion that we
&ldquo;perceive&rdquo; &ldquo;[<em>w</em>]<em>hatever</em> happens
in&rdquo; that body (E2p12, emphasis added). Prima facie this
proposition ascribes, implausibly, a godlike omniscience to human
minds. Experience clearly tells against such a proposal: we certainly
aren&rsquo;t aware of <em>all</em> of the affections of our bodies
(i.e., of all that &ldquo;happens in&rdquo; them), down to the
cellular (and even quantum) level of each organ. It&rsquo;s much more
plausible to take Spinoza&rsquo;s claim to be that we have such
perceptions, but their utter confusedness or lack of clarity and
distinctness makes them indiscernible to us.</p>

<p>
The initial, highly implausible appearance of E2p12 dissolves even
further once we make note of Spinoza&rsquo;s <em>functional</em>
understanding of bodies: not everything that <em>we</em> might
ordinarily consider a &ldquo;part&rdquo; of a body falls under this
concept for Spinoza (cf. Donagan 1988:123):</p>

<blockquote>
parts composing the human Body pertain to the essence of the Body
itself only insofar as they communicate their motions to one another
in a certain fixed manner&hellip;and not insofar as they can be
considered as Individuals, without relation to the human Body.
(E2p24d)
</blockquote>

<p>
Accordingly, Spinoza will have a suitably narrower understanding of
the scope of &ldquo;whatever happens in&rdquo; the parts of our own
bodies: we will &ldquo;perceive&rdquo; only those affections of the
pancreas, say (to use Della Rocca&rsquo;s example [2018]), that bear
on the whole body&rsquo;s ability to function as an integrated
organism (cf. Garrett 2018: ch.14).</p>

<p>
Even if we manage to make sense of the apparent ascription of bodily
omniscience to human minds, at least two other problems for
Spinoza&rsquo;s account of the mind-body relation remain.</p>

<p>
First, although tying the individuation of certain &ldquo;parts&rdquo;
of the infinite intellect to certain bits of reality that these parts
essentially represent may well solve the problem of individuating
finite minds in a substance-monistic framework (see 2.1.2), it also
seems to generate a new problem. This is that to explain the nature of
the human mind we must now appeal to the existence of
<em>bodies</em>:</p>

<blockquote>
to determine what is the difference between the human Mind and the
others, and how it surpasses them, it is necessary for us, as we have
said, to know the nature of its object, i.e., of the human body
(E2p13s)
</blockquote>

<p>
The problem is that, as we know (1.2), Spinoza <em>prohibits</em>
cross-attribute explanations: no physical thing can explain anything
mental, and vice versa. Yet Spinoza&rsquo;s own account of the
essential constitution of human minds seems not just to <em>allow</em>
for such cross-attribute explanations, but to <em>require</em>
them.</p>

<p>
Here is another interpretative problem that seems to plague
Spinoza&rsquo;s account of the human mind. How should we understand
the relation between 1) the intentional or representational relation
that human minds essentially bear to bodies, and 2) Spinoza&rsquo;s
claim that minds and bodies are &ldquo;one and the same thing&rdquo;
(E2p7s)? The doctrine of mind-body identity seems to follow directly
for Spinoza from <em>substance&rsquo;s</em> identity under different
attributes: since thinking substance and extended substance are in
fact just a single substance considered or described in two different
ways, so also all of substance&rsquo;s <em>modifications</em> will be
subject to that same sort of multiplicity of descriptions.
Accordingly, the human mind and the human body are numerically
&ldquo;one and the same thing&rdquo; (namely, a certain finite mode)
but this mode can be veridically described as a mind <em>or</em> as a
body. But when we pair this doctrine of mind-body identity with the
thesis of an essential representational relation between the mind and
the body, we are faced with the question, Why should a mind represent
what it is numerically identical with, or be identical with what it
represents? How do we make this twofold nature of the mind-body
relation intelligible?</p>

<p>
(On mind-body identity, see e.g. Delahunty 1985; Della Rocca 1996;
Jarrett 1991; C. Marshall 2009; on its relation to mind-body
intentionality, Garrett 2018: ch.15; H&uuml;bner 2022; for solutions
to the barrier violation, e.g. Della Rocca 1996, H&uuml;bner 2022,
2019.)</p>

<h3 id="ConsIdeaIdea">2.3 Consciousness and ideas of ideas</h3>

<p>
Given the importance of the concept of consciousness to contemporary
philosophy of mind, it is perhaps unsurprising that readers have tried
to extract a theory of consciousness also from the rare appearances of
terms such as <em>conscius</em> and <em>conscientia</em> in Spinoza&rsquo;s
writings. Such efforts are also unsurprising given Spinoza&rsquo;s
historical placement between Descartes (often taken to define thought
in terms of consciousness) and Leibniz (who distinguishes thinking as
a perfectly general property from consciousness as a property of
higher minds alone) (cf. LeBuffe 2010). Interpreters return again and
again to certain questions: did Spinoza even <em>have</em> a theory of
consciousness in a recognizable sense? If he did, was it an internally
consistent and adequately defended theory? Was it meant to distinguish
conscious and unconscious ideas (and so also conscious and unconscious
minds [see 2.1.1])? Did Spinoza posit universal (but perhaps scalar or
graded) consciousness, just as he posited universal (but scalar or
graded) mindedness (see 2.1.3)?</p>

<p>
The existing array of interpretations ranges widely, from
Curley&rsquo;s 1969 conclusion that for Spinoza
&ldquo;consciousness&rdquo; picks out <em>higher order</em> ideas
(that is, ideas of ideas); through proposals that the term is intended
to track the <em>complexity</em> of ideas (Nadler 2008) or their
<em>power</em> (D. Garrett 2018: ch.14, E. Marshall 2013); to the
claim that Spinoza uses <em>conscius</em> and <em>conscientia</em> in
several different senses (LeBuffe 2010b).</p>

<p>
The ideas-of-ideas reading of consciousness gets going because of
passages like E4p8d, where Spinoza characterizes
&ldquo;cognition&rdquo; of good and evil as
&ldquo;consciousness&rdquo; of certain emotions (given that
Spinozistic emotions or &ldquo;affects&rdquo; are already themselves
constituted in part by &ldquo;ideas&rdquo; [E3def3]) and E3p9s, where
Spinoza characterizes &ldquo;desire&rdquo; as &ldquo;appetite together
with consciousness of appetite&rdquo; (given that
&ldquo;appetite&rdquo; is already &ldquo;related to the mind&rdquo;
[E3p9s]). In both cases the implication seems to be that consciousness
is or involves higher-order ideas. And Spinoza understands ideas of
ideas not as numerically distinct from the first-order ideas, but
rather as <em>ways of</em> <em>regarding</em> the first-order ideas:
an idea of idea <em>A</em> is just <em>A</em> considered only as an
<em>act</em> of thinking (leaving aside its representational content).
That is, to use Spinoza&rsquo;s Scholastic terminology, it is the original
idea considered in its &ldquo;formal reality&rdquo; alone: it is
&ldquo;the form of the idea&hellip;considered as a mode of thinking
without relation to the object&rdquo; (E2p21s).</p>

<p>
This interpretation of consciousness in terms of ideas-of-ideas is of
no use to someone looking to Spinoza for a theory of
<em>selective</em> consciousness, on which consciousness distinguishes
some mental states from others. This is because in Spinoza&rsquo;s
framework there is no idea of which there is no higher-order idea.
This follows from divine omniscience: an all-knowing God has ideas of
all things, including all ideas.</p>

<p>
Interpretations on which consciousness is instead a scalar property
tracking complexity or power fare much better in accounting for texts
in which Spinoza depicts consciousness as a matter of selective causal
and cognitive achievement, as in the following:</p>

<blockquote>
He who, like an infant or child, has a body capable of very few things
and very heavily dependent on external causes, has a mind which
considered solely in itself is conscious of almost nothing of itself,
or of God, or of things. On the other hand, he who has a body capable
of a great many things, has a mind which considered only in itself is
very much conscious of itself, and of God, and of things (E5p39s)
</blockquote>

<p>
(On consciousness see also Miller 2007.)</p>

<h3 id="WillAffi">2.4 Willing or affirming</h3>

<p>
In contrast to consciousness, the will is a subject on which Spinoza&rsquo;s
convictions are loud and clear. His account of willing is developed in
opposition to Descartes&rsquo;s account, on several fronts. First, and
perhaps most famously, Spinoza denies that human beings have a
<em>free</em> (undetermined) will (E1app; G/II/78). The freedom that
Descartes finds undeniable in introspection is for Spinoza only a
manifestation of the depths of our ignorance about how we actually
have been determined to act. Second, Descartes had proposed that we
distinguish intellect as a faculty for forming representations, from
will as a faculty for judging the truth value of these
representations. Spinoza rejects both the idea that there <em>are</em>
any faculties over and above particular ideas and volitions (cf.
2.1.1), and the separation of the representational and volitional
elements. Instead he proposes that we see the volitional element as
<em>intrinsic</em> to representation, such that we &ldquo;affirm
insofar as [we] perceiv[e]&rdquo; (E2p49s [III.B(ii)]; G/II/134). In
consequence Spinozistic ideas are <em>belief-like:</em> they
&ldquo;affirm&rdquo; &ndash; posit the existence of &ndash; the things
they represent. On this picture, in thinking of my dog, for example, I
thereby affirm her existence.</p>

<p>
One obvious objection a Cartesian might make to this account is that
it seems incapable of explaining the familiar experience of merely
entertaining (imagining, hypothesizing, exploring, etc.) some idea
without committing ourselves to its truth or falsity, or to the
existence of the represented object. As Spinoza puts the objection in
the mouth of an imaginary opponent,</p>

<blockquote>
someone who feigns a winged horse does not on that account grant that
there is a winged horse, i.e., he is not on that account
deceived&hellip;Therefore, experience seems to teach&hellip;that the
will, or faculty of assenting, is free, and different from the faculty
of understanding. (E2p49s [III.A.(ii)])
</blockquote>

<p>
To fend off this objection Spinoza must find a way of explaining the
possibility of representing something (such as a winged horse) without
committing to its existence, while drawing solely on the resources of
his particular, intrinsically affirmative ideas. His proposal focuses
on <em>countervailing</em> or offsetting ideas: ideas that affirm or
posit something that negates or &ldquo;excludes
[<em>tollere</em>]&rdquo; the existence of an object represented by
other ideas. For example, a child &ldquo;imagining a winged horse, and
not perceiving anything else&hellip;that excludes the existence of the
horse&hellip;.will necessarily regard the horse as present&rdquo;
(E2p49s [III.B.(ii)]; G/II/134). But, with some schooling, the
child&rsquo;s original idea of a winged horse can be offset by another
idea (say, by the rational representation of equine bones as, in
general, too heavy to be lifted by feathers). Spinoza&rsquo;s proposal
explains not only how the ordinary experience of mere entertainment of
ideas is possible, but also offers a genealogy of <em>negation</em> as
a mental operation posterior to affirmation (cf. Donagan 1988:46): it
is only if we form multiple, mutually inconsistent affirmative ideas,
that we can negate the contents of one or more of these ideas.</p>

<p>
The obvious question this reconstruction of Spinoza&rsquo;s account
raises is why, in cases of mental conflict, in which certain ideas
&ldquo;exclude&rdquo; other ideas, should one of these ideas
ultimately prevail? As Diane Steinberg notes, Spinoza cannot have in
mind a purely <em>logical</em> inconsistency or contradiction between
ideas, since this doesn&rsquo;t yet give us a reason to nonarbitrarily
prefer one idea over another (2003). The psychology of
&ldquo;exclusion&rdquo; must thus involve not merely logical
incompatibility of contents, but something that would asymmetrically
tip the scales in favor of one idea or another. Commentators have
proposed that greater causal <em>power</em> as the best candidate for
this role: the winning idea is the idea with more power to continue
existing and to produce further ideas (in short, greater power to
&ldquo;strive&rdquo; [E3p7]), or greater power to determine the
mind&rsquo;s activity or causal power as a whole (e.g. Della Rocca
2003; J. Steinberg 2018b).</p>

<p>
(On affirmation, will and excluding ideas see also 3.2.2. On
&ldquo;fictions&rdquo;, see e.g. Barry 2019, 2021, D. Garrett 2018:
ch. 5, J. Steinberg 2018b; on striving, see e.g. Carriero 2011, Kisner
2011, LeBuffe 2010, Viljanen 2011, Youpa 2020 and entry on
 <a href="../spinoza-psychological/">Spinoza&rsquo;s psychological theory</a>.)</p>
 
<h2 id="Epis">3. Epistemology</h2>

<h3 id="TrutAdeq">3.1 Truth and adequacy</h3>

<p>
Spinoza pronounces on the nature of truth in one of his earliest
axioms in the <em>Ethics</em>: &ldquo;A true idea must agree with
[<em>convenire</em>] its object&rdquo; (E1ax6). It has led many
readers to interpret Spinoza as a correspondence theorist of truth,
that is, as endorsing the view that truth consists in some sort of
conformity&ndash;&ldquo;agreement&rdquo;&ndash;of thought with
reality.</p>

<p>
However, this relational property of &ldquo;agreement&rdquo; is not
the only way Spinoza characterizes truth. True Spinozistic ideas also
have an <em>intrinsic</em> and, arguably, introspectable (cf. Garrett
2018: ch.5) property which distinguishes them as true without
requiring us to look beyond the ideas themselves. An
&ldquo;adequate&rdquo; idea is one with this intrinsic property:</p>

<blockquote>
By adequate idea I understand an idea which, insofar as it is
considered in itself, without relation to an object, has all the
properties, or intrinsic denominations of a true idea. <em>Exp</em>.:
say intrinsic to exclude what is extrinsic, viz. the agreement of the
idea with its object. (E2def4)
</blockquote>

<p>
Consequently, truth can be &ldquo;its own standard&rdquo;, such that
&ldquo;he who has a true idea at the same time knows that he has a
true idea, and cannot doubt the truth of the thing&rdquo; (E2p43, cf.
TIE &sect;36).</p>

<p>
The view is surely puzzling: How is it that just by considering an
idea on its own, we can be certain that it in fact conforms to what it
represents? What might these intrinsic signs of truth be?</p>

<p>
One plausible answer is that Spinoza has in mind here something like
clarity and distinctness (cf. e.g. E2p38c), and so is in broad
agreement with Descartes&rsquo;s &ldquo;rule&rdquo; that true ideas
can appear to us as clear and distinct. Don Garrett has suggested
that, in addition to clarity and distinctness, we should understand
adequacy as the &ldquo;logical consistency of the represented
object&rdquo; (2018: ch.6). On this reading, true ideas are
self-evidently true insofar as we can clearly and distinctly perceive
the logical consistency of what they represent. This proposal has the
virtue of tying together Spinoza&rsquo;s two characterizations of
truth &ndash; the extrinsic and the intrinsic one &ndash; into one
neat package: given Spinoza&rsquo;s commitment to necessitarianism
(E1p33, E1p35), any logically consistent idea will represent not just
a possible object but a necessary and actual one; hence we can know
from the logical consistency of an idea alone that it in fact
corresponds to its object.</p>

<p>
The above definition of adequate idea in terms of a true idea&rsquo;s
intrinsic or nonrelational properties is, however, not the only way
Spinoza characterizes &ldquo;adequacy&rdquo;. He also gives what we
could call a <em>mind-relative</em> account of adequacy. It is made
possible by his aforementioned belief that finite minds are
&ldquo;parts&rdquo; of the omniscient &ldquo;infinite intellect&rdquo;
(see 2.1.2). As he explains, &ldquo;there are no inadequate or
confused ideas except insofar as they are related to the singular mind
of someone&rdquo; (E2p36d):</p>

<blockquote>
when we say that God has this or that idea, not only insofar as he
constitutes the nature of the human Mind, but insofar as he also has
the idea of another thing together with the human Mind, then we say
that the human Mind perceives the thing only partially, <em>or</em>
inadequately (E2p11c)
</blockquote>

<p>
In other words, if ideas constituting a given finite mind suffice for
representing <em>x</em> in the same way that a perfect knower would
represent <em>x</em>, the mind in question represents <em>x</em>
&ldquo;adequately&rdquo;. Gwendolyn Marshall has usefully expressed
this point in terms of part-whole &ldquo;containment&rdquo;: ideas are
adequate iff they are entirely a part of, i.e., contained in, the
relevant finite mind (2013:26).</p>

<p>
Here is an example of how this might work. Consider once again
Spinoza&rsquo;s claim that the idea of the body that essentially
constitutes a human mind is experienced as &ldquo;completely
confused&rdquo; (see 2.2.1). We can put this point in terms of
<em>inadequacy</em>: a human mind knows its body as a particular in
duration only by perceiving how it is &ldquo;affected&rdquo; or
changed. This idea of the body is &ldquo;inadequate&rdquo; in
Spinoza&rsquo;s technical sense because God&rsquo;s conception of that
body includes many components that are not also part of the human
mind&rsquo;s conception of it: God conceives of all the many bodies
that go into composing, preserving, and &ldquo;regenerating&rdquo; the
affected human body, as well as all the affecting external bodies, and
the infinite series of causes on which these bodies depend (E2p19d).
One might wonder if finite minds like ours can ever manage to think
anything truly &ldquo;adequately&rdquo;, if this requires that
<em>all</em> of the &ldquo;premises&rdquo; of a given idea be
contained in our minds (cf. Della Rocca 1996; we come back to this
question in 3.2.1.)</p>

<p>
Confronted with Spinoza&rsquo;s account of adequacy, we might also
wonder how his two characterizations of this concept are supposed to
hang together: why should an idea entirely contained in a mind also
have certain intrinsic markings of truth, such as clarity and
distinctness? One way to reconcile these two claims is to infer that
for Spinoza only ideas whose &ldquo;premises&rdquo;, so to speak, are
wholly contained in a given mind can also appear as manifestly or
self-evidently true. This would be to understand the self-evidence of
adequate ideas not as a property of individual ideas, but more
holistically, as a property they acquire as a certain connection or
ordering of ideas.</p>

<p>
Finally, some commentators haved added a third characterization of
adequate ideas, proposing that an &ldquo;adequate&rdquo; idea is
contained in a mind insofar as it has been &ldquo;adequately
caused&rdquo; &ndash; i.e., self-sufficiently or autonomously caused
&ndash; by the mind in question. Such an idea would then count as a
true &ldquo;action&rdquo; of that mind, in Spinoza&rsquo;s technical
sense of this term (E3def1&ndash;2). If that proposal is right, then
adequate ideas must all also be <em>innate</em> (LeBuffe 2010, G.
Marshall 2013, J. Steinberg 2018a: ch.8). For having a cause external
to the mind &ndash; for example, arising from experience &ndash; would
be incompatible by definition with having been &ldquo;adequately
caused&rdquo;. On such readings, what we might experience as an
<em>acquisition</em> of an adequate idea (say, in a philosophy class)
is in fact only a matter of becoming <em>more conscious</em> of it (J.
Steinberg 2018a: ch.8; see 2.3).</p>

<p>
(See also Kisner 2011.)</p>

<h3 id="KnowCogn">3.2 Knowledge (<em>cognitio</em>)</h3>

<p>
The common English translation of Spinoza&rsquo;s <em>cognitio</em> as
&ldquo;knowledge&rdquo; does not do justice to his understanding of
the term. For &ldquo;<em>cognitio</em>&rdquo; includes not just true
and adequate ideas, but also false and inadequate ones. This entry
will therefore opt for using &ldquo;cognition&rdquo; as the default
translation.</p>

<h4 id="CognCaus">3.2.1 Cognition and causation</h4>

<p>
One of the most important epistemological principles standardly
ascribed to Spinoza is that to cognize <em>x</em>, one must cognize
its <em>causes</em>. This principle is the subject of another early
axiom, E1ax4: &ldquo;Cognition of an effect depends on, and involves,
cognition of its cause&rdquo; (transl. alt., cf. TIE[85]). That axiom
in turn is the key premise of what has come to be known as
Spinoza&rsquo;s &ldquo;parallelism doctrine&rdquo;, the proposition
stating that &ldquo;The order and connection of ideas is the same as
the order and connection of things&rdquo; (E2p7). Spinoza&rsquo;s
appeal to E1ax4 in the demonstration of this proposition makes clear
that the &ldquo;order and connection of things&rdquo; he has in mind
in E2p7 is a <em>causal</em> order and connection (cf.
E2p9d). The idea is that, at least for an omniscient
&ldquo;infinite intellect&rdquo;, connections between ideas of things
perfectly mirror the causal connections between those things in nature
(cf. TIE &sect;&sect;91, 99).</p>

<p>
There are several interpretative puzzles attached to E1ax4 and the
principle it expresses. One puzzle is purely metaphysical: what sorts
of causes, out of the rich panoply envisioned by the Aristotelians,
might Spinoza allow in his metaphysics? The second puzzle concerns the
<em>kind of cognition</em> at stake in E1ax4. Some readers (e.g.,
Bennett 1984; Gueroult 1969) have proposed that the axiom governs
<em>adequate</em> cognition alone. So understood, the axiom expresses
a version of the traditional view that truly &ldquo;scientific&rdquo;
knowledge requires a knowledge of causes &ndash; the knowledge
<em>why</em> something happened, not merely <em>that</em> it happened.
But, as Margaret Wilson has pointed out (1999: ch.10), this restricted
reading of the scope of the axiom can&rsquo;t be correct, since in
Spinoza&rsquo;s view even <em>inadequate</em> ideas formed in sense
experience &ldquo;involve&rdquo; their causes. (For example, the
inadequate knowledge I have of any bodily change
&ldquo;involves&rdquo; the inadequate knowledge of its external cause
[E2ax1&rsquo;, E2p25, E2p28].)</p>

<p>
A third interpretive puzzle concerns the meaning of the two terms
&ndash; &ldquo;dependence&rdquo; and &ldquo;involvement&rdquo; &ndash;
used by Spinoza to characterize the relation between causes and
cognitions in E1ax4. &ldquo;Involvement&rdquo; is most often glossed
as &ldquo;implication&rdquo;. But Wilson has argued that in key
passages (e.g. E2p45) <em>involvere</em> stands more specifically for
the relation of implication between an <em>attribute</em> concept
(e.g. <em>extension, thought</em>) and cognition of a mode (1999:
ch.10). On this reading of &ldquo;involvement&rdquo;, Spinoza&rsquo;s
claim in E1ax4 that cognition of effects &ldquo;involves&rdquo; a
cognition of causes amounts to the relatively intuitive claim that
conceiving of extension or thought is necessary for conceiving of any
particular mind or body. So understood, the axiom doesn&rsquo;t direct
us to discover the causes of things so that we may have truly
scientific knowledge of them, but instead merely describes what is
entailed by even the most minimal and inadequate conception of
anything whatsoever. The fourth puzzle is this: it&rsquo;s not clear
how to reconcile this causal principle with Spinoza&rsquo;s account of
the human mind. For, as we saw (2.2), cognition of the essence of
human minds requires reference to actually existing bodies; yet, given
Spinoza&rsquo;s commitment to the attribute barrier (1.2), bodies
cannot stand in a causal relation to anything mental. So either
Spinoza&rsquo;s account of the human mind is invalid by his own lights
or (more likely) Spinoza also allows for cognitions that do
<em>not</em> &ldquo;involve&rdquo; a thing&rsquo;s causes.</p>

<p>
Finally, to pick up a problem flagged in 3.1, since each finite thing
depends on an &ldquo;infinite&rdquo; series of prior finite causes
(E1p28), if &ldquo;adequate&rdquo; cognition of a thing requires a
grasp of <em>all</em> its causes, this would put an implausible,
&ldquo;stratospherically high&rdquo; (Bennett 1984) requirement on
cognition. Indeed it would presumably put such cognition outside the
reach of minds like ours, since, as Spinoza admits, we simply cannot
know the entire infinite series of finite things responsible for any
given state of affairs in nature (TIE &sect;100). Here Wilson&rsquo;s
insight about how Spinoza uses &ldquo;involvement&rdquo; is helpful:
we <em>can</em> have adequate causal cognition of particular things,
as long as we look to God (the first and universal cause of all
things) and not to the infinite series of prior <em>finite</em> things
as the relevant cause, and as long as we attempt to explain the
<em>essences</em> of particulars, not their durational states.
Spinoza&rsquo;s doctrine of &ldquo;common notions&rdquo; (see 3.2.3)
guarantees that we have adequate ideas of God under the attributes of
extension and thought. And to know God as the cause of the essence of
a particular thing is just to have what Spinoza calls &ldquo;intuitive
cognition&rdquo; (see 3.2.5.)</p>

<p>
(On causal cognition, see e.g. Koistinen 1996, Morrison 2013, 2015,
Nelson 2025; on reconciling it with mind-body account, Della Rocca
1996, H&uuml;bner 2021; on possibility of adequate cognition, e.g. G.
Marshall 2013.)</p>

<h4 id="KindCognIImagFals">3.2.2 Kinds of cognition I: Imagination and falsity</h4>

<p>
Spinoza divides possible cognition into three kinds: imagination;
reason [<em>ratio</em>]; and intuition [<em>scientia intuitiva</em>].
This section focuses on the first of these.</p>

<p>
First, a terminological warning: what Spinoza calls
&ldquo;imagination&rdquo; shouldn&rsquo;t be confused with what
<em>we</em> are likely to mean by that term today. By
<em>imaginatio</em> Spinoza understands first and foremost sense
experience (including cognition from signs and testimony) and
derivative mental processes (including memory and the sort of
manipulation of mental imagery that we might today call
&ldquo;imagination&rdquo;). &ldquo;Image&rdquo; is another potential
terminological trap for today&rsquo;s readers: it&rsquo;s
Spinoza&rsquo;s label for something <em>physical</em>, a modification
of the body. In contrast, &ldquo;imagination&rdquo; names something
mental: the act or operation of representing, or forming ideas of,
such physical &ldquo;images&rdquo;.</p>

<p>
Spinozistic <em>imaginatio</em> is distinct from other kinds of
cognition in virtue of both its content and its causes. First,
imagination is cognition of <em>external</em> <em>bodies</em> as
<em>present;</em> second, it is cognition acquired through ideas of
our own bodily<em> affections</em> (i.e., changes or modifications)
caused by other bodies:</p>

<blockquote>
affections of the human body whose ideas present external bodies as
present to us, we shall call images of things, even if they do not
reproduce the [NS: external] figures of things. And when the mind
regards bodies in this way, we shall say that it imagines (E2p17s;
G/II/106)
</blockquote>

<p>
One of the most important claims Spinoza makes about imaginative
cognition is that it comprises &ldquo;all those ideas which are
inadequate and confused and so&hellip;is the only cause of
falsity&rdquo; (E2p41d). That is, only ideas derived from sense
experience can <em>give rise</em> to false beliefs &ndash; that is, as we
saw in 3.1., to ideas that affirm the existence of non-existent
objects, but which have not been correctly offset or counteracted by
other ideas. The list of objects of which, Spinoza thinks, we have
only such inadequate and confused cognition is staggering: it includes
our own bodies; external bodies; the affections, parts, and durations
of both; finally, even our minds (E2p19&ndash;31) (cf. 2.2.1). As
Spinoza concludes pessimistically, &ldquo;all the notions by which
ordinary people are accustomed to explain nature are only modes of
imagining, and do not indicate the nature of anything&rdquo; (E1app;
G/II/83).</p>

<p>
What sort of &ldquo;confusion&rdquo; does Spinoza have in mind when he
says that imagination comprises &ldquo;all &lsquo;inadequate and
confused&rsquo; ideas, therefore all ideas capable of giving rise to
&lsquo;false&rsquo; beliefs&rdquo; (E2p41d)? Recall that imaginative
cognition consists in ideas of affections of (changes in) our own
bodies. According to Spinoza, such ideas also present us, indirectly,
with the <em>external</em> <em>causes</em> of the affections in
question. (As Spinoza puts it, all our ideas of externally-caused
affections of our own bodies &ldquo;involve&rdquo; the nature of the
external cause [E2p16].) So the &ldquo;confusion&rdquo; inherent to
imaginative cognition seems to do with the fact that imaginative ideas
have a content that is an <em>amalgam</em> of two distinct things: the
current condition of some part of my body <em>and</em> the external
cause (E2p16, E2p25; cf. Della Rocca 1996). For example, when my hand
is warmed by the sun, the nature of that bodily change depends on the
nature of the sun <em>together with</em> the nature and current state
of that part of my body. My perception of the bodily affection &ndash;
of the increased warmth &ndash; tells me <em>something</em> both about
my own body and about the sun: I have some insight into one or more of
the <em>relative</em> properties of both things. But it doesn&rsquo;t
tell me about the intrinsic or essential nature either of my own body
or the sun. It also doesn&rsquo;t allow me to clearly <em>distinguish
</em>the relative contributions of the external cause and of my own
body. (Indeed, Spinoza goes so far as to propose that that such ideas
&ldquo;indicate the condition of our own body <em>more</em>
<em>than</em> the nature of the external bodies&rdquo; [E2p16c2;
emphasis added].)</p>

<p>
What about Spinoza&rsquo;s characterization of imaginative ideas as
&ldquo;inadequate&rdquo; (E2p41d)? Recall that &ldquo;adequate&rdquo;
ideas are <em>manifestly true</em> ideas that are also <em>fully
explained by the mind</em> they help constitute (3.1). So, first, a
<em>lack</em> of adequacy is a lack of an intrinsic marker of truth,
and hence of <em>certainty</em> that we are dealing with true ideas.
Of course, we may stumble on the right result (as when we correctly
apply a memorized mathematical rule accepted on authority [cf.
E2p40s2]). But we cannot yet be sure that our ideas manage to
&ldquo;agree&rdquo; with, or correspond to, reality.</p>

<p>
Second, the mind thinking the imaginative ideas in question will not
be capable of fully accounting for those ideas: it won&rsquo;t possess all
of their &ldquo;premises&rdquo;. Instead, the imaginative ideas in
question will have been produced by, and so will also conceptually
&ldquo;involve&rdquo;, the natures of the external causes that brought
about the relevant affections of the body. So instead of being orderly
connected to all their premises in the mind (according to what Spinoza
calls the &ldquo;order of the intellect, by which the Mind perceives
things through their first causes, and which is the same in all
men&rdquo; [E2p18s]), imaginative ideas will be connected to one
another in that mind according to the &ldquo;common order of
Nature&rdquo; (E2p29s), that is, in a way that reflects the order of
our happenstance encounters with other bodies, and the idiosyncratic
psychological associations such encounters generate:</p>

<blockquote>
For example, a soldier, having seen traces of a horse in the sand,
will immediately pass from the thought of a horse to the thought of a
horseman, and from that to the thought of war, etc. But a Farmer will
pass from the thought of a horse to the thought of a plow, and then to
that of a field, etc. And so each one, according as he has been
accustomed to join and connect the images of things in this or that
way, will pass from one thought to another. (E2p18s)
</blockquote>

<p>
It is fairly easy to see how ideas whose premises are only partially
grasped, and which are haphazardly connected together, could become a
&ldquo;cause of falsity&rdquo; &ndash; that is, could easily generate
erroneous inferences and associations, as long as we have not yet
grasped ideas that would be needed to offset or &ldquo;exclude&rdquo;
(see 2.4) such erroneous inferences and associations:</p>

<blockquote>
the mind does not err from the fact that it imagines, but only insofar
as it is considered to lack an idea which excludes the existence of
those things which it imagines to be present to it (E2p17s).
</blockquote>

<p>
To take an example important for the history of philosophy, on
Spinoza&rsquo;s analysis, our belief in a &ldquo;free will&rdquo; is a
false belief that follows from sense experience that has not been
offset by countervailing ideas: it arises because &ldquo;we are
conscious of [our] actions and ignorant of [their] causes&rdquo;
(E2p35s). Any perception of my own action will be
&ldquo;inadequate&rdquo; (i.e., merely partial or
&ldquo;mutilated&rdquo;, by comparison to God&rsquo;s infallible idea
of that same action) if the ideas of all the necessitating causes of
that action are not also part of my mind. Such a
&ldquo;mutilated&rdquo; and so &ldquo;inadequate&rdquo; idea of my own
action can generate a false belief in free will as long as I lack
offsetting ideas &ndash; say, of the <em>general</em> necessity of all
actions in nature (e.g. E1p33), together with an understanding of
<em>myself</em> as subject to the very same laws as any other natural
thing (E3pref; G/II/138).</p>

<p>
This picture of falsehood as the result of the confusion and
inadequacy of ideas generated by sense experience, combined with the
absence of countervailing ideas, is behind Spinoza&rsquo;s claim that
&ldquo;falsity&rdquo; is &ldquo;nothing positive&rdquo;, only a
relative &ldquo;privation of knowledge&rdquo; (E2p35) about the matter
at hand. (Falsity so understood must also be distinguished from an
&ldquo;absolute&rdquo; &ldquo;ignorance&rdquo; of something
[E2p35d].)</p>

<p>
The lack of ideas that could exclude or offset false conclusions
carries another epistemic danger, and contributes to the loss of our
&ldquo;power&rdquo; to think in yet another way: any ideas we have
failed to exclude lie in the mind ready to be combined with any
<em>adequate</em> ideas we&rsquo;ve managed to secure, thereby
undermining the epistemic good that the latter bring with them. For
example, if we have not yet excluded the ideas of <em>divine</em>
<em>goodness</em> or <em>divine</em> <em>purposiveness</em> from our
minds (see E1app), we can easily &ldquo;join&rdquo; such inadequate
ideas to the adequate idea that, Spinoza assures us, <em>every</em>
mind has of God (E2p46-7).</p>

<h4 id="KindCognIIInteCommNotiReas">3.2.3 Kinds of cognition II: Intellect, common notions, and reason</h4>

<p>
Spinoza contrasts confused, inadequate, and falsehood-courting
imagination with &ldquo;intellect&rdquo;, which he subdivides into
&ldquo;reason&rdquo; and &ldquo;intuition&rdquo;. Given
Spinoza&rsquo;s bundle-theoretic approach to minds (2.1.1), talk of
&ldquo;intellect&rdquo; is not intended to conjure up here any sort of
mental &ldquo;faculty&rdquo; over and above particular ideas.
&ldquo;Intellect&rdquo; is instead Spinoza&rsquo;s name for a certain
type of cognition, namely one that is &ldquo;necessarily true&rdquo;
(E2p41). That is, intellectual ideas necessarily &ldquo;agree&rdquo;
with, or correspond to, represented objects (E1ax6; see 3.1). This
&ldquo;agreement&rdquo; with the causal order of things in nature
allows intellectual ideas to be &ldquo;the same in all&rdquo; minds
(E2p18s). Intellectual ideas are also &ldquo;adequate&rdquo; (E2p41d),
that is, manifestly true and fully explained by the mind they help
constitute (3.1). Because intellectual ideas of truth and falsity in
particular are manifestly true, intellectual cognition enables us to
&ldquo;distinguish the true from the false&rdquo; with certainty
(E2p42).</p>

<p>
So how do we get our hands on this cornucopia of epistemic goods?
Spinoza warns that &ldquo;ideas which are clear and distinct in
us&rdquo; (i.e., manifestly true or &ldquo;adequate&rdquo;)
&ldquo;<em>cannot</em> follow from mutilated and confused ideas&rdquo;
(E5p28d; emphasis added). This would seem to <em>preclude</em> any
possibility of progressing from imagination to intellect. Fortunately
Spinoza leaves us an escape hatch in the form of &ldquo;common
notions&rdquo;, which he calls, appropriately, the
&ldquo;foundations&rdquo; of reason, i.e., of the first of the two
kinds of intellectual cognition (E2p40s1). We may not be able to
generate clear and distinct ideas from <em>confused</em> ideas, but
not all is yet lost, because according to Spinoza even brute sense
experience furnishes us with <em>some</em> necessarily adequate ideas
(or, on innatist readings [see 3.1], triggers or activates such
ideas).</p>

<p>
More precisely, in Spinoza&rsquo;s view, in every encounter with
another thing, not matter how confused my ideas of both my own body
and the external body (3.2.2), I also form <em>necessarily
adequate</em> ideas of any properties that are both 1)
&ldquo;common&rdquo; to the interacting bodies and 2) &ldquo;equally
in the part and in the whole&rdquo; (E2p38). That is, I form
necessarily adequate ideas of any properties wholly and without
distinction present in each particular thing. For example, the
property of being <em>extended</em> is one such property: extension is
extension is extension, whether it belongs to me or to a mosquito
biting me; I am neither more nor less of a physical thing than a
mosquito is. Likewise, every body possesses the property of having a
capacity for &ldquo;motion and rest&rdquo; (&ldquo;all bodies
agree&hellip;in that they can move now more slowly, now more quickly,
and that now they move, now they are at rest&rdquo; [E2Ld]). For
Spinoza, all such properties that are both universally instantiated
(&ldquo;common&rdquo; to all things) and non scalar (&ldquo;equally in
the part and in the whole&rdquo;) are necessarily grasped correctly by
<em>any</em> mind. And all ideas of such common properties &ndash; all
&ldquo;common notions&rdquo; &ndash; are necessarily adequate.</p>

<p>
What is Spinoza&rsquo;s argument for this rather implausible claim,
that we simply cannot get certain properties (such as extension,
thought, motion and rest) <em>wrong</em>? As we have seen, a lot
hinges on this doctrine: nothing less than the very possibility of
intellectual emendation, of transcending the confusion and inadequacy
of mere imagination. The answer has to do with how Spinoza thinks
about what is responsible for the <em>absence</em> of adequacy. As we
saw above (3.2.2), in his view, any ideas of external bodies that I
form through mere sense experience will in fact be ideas of how those
bodies affect me. (For example, my empirical idea of <em>the sun</em>
in fact only represents one way that the sun can affect my body in its
current state.) But common properties like extension are
&ldquo;equally in the part and in the whole&rdquo;: wholly and without
distinction in each thing. So for the adequacy of my idea of the sun
<em>as extended</em> it does not matter if I&rsquo;m representing
extension as it is in the sun, or as it is in my body, or as it is in
the &ldquo;confused&rdquo; amalgam of the two. Extension is extension
is extension. Because common notions are insulated against error in
this way, and because no idea inferable from an adequate idea can
itself be inadequate (E2p40), these notions can indeed form a
&ldquo;foundation&rdquo; of reasoning, and so be our entry into the
realm of intellect.</p>

<p>
What is sometimes overlooked in discussions of common notions is that
Spinoza seems to allow for <em>two kinds</em> of common notions: what
we could call 1) <em>universal</em> common notions, notions of truly
universally instantiated non-scalar properties, such as extension; and
what we could call 2) <em>relative</em> common notions, ideas of
properties &ldquo;common to, and peculiar to [<em>proprium</em>], the
human body and certain external bodies by which the human Body is
usually affected [<em>affici solet</em>], and is equally in the part
and in the whole of each of them&rdquo; (E2p39). The principle of the
necessary adequacy of such &lsquo;relative&rsquo; common notions is presumably the
same: if some property genuinely exists in very same way in me and in
my usual physical environment, it does not matter if I represent this
property as it is in me or as it is in my environment, or finally as
it is in the &ldquo;confused&rdquo; amalgam of the two. But it&rsquo;s
also not obvious what to make of Spinoza&rsquo;s characterization of this
second type of common notion. What counts as being
&ldquo;peculiar&rdquo; to what &ldquo;usually&rdquo; affects us? For
example, are the general ideas Spinoza relies on in his account of
&ldquo;human&rdquo; emotions (&ldquo;affects&rdquo;), and our
&ldquo;bondage&rdquo; to them, common notions in this relative sense?
We could pose a similar question about <em>universal</em> common
notions: what else should we include in a list of universal common
notions, beyond the fairly uncontroversial examples of extension,
thought, and motion-and-rest?</p>

<p>
One interesting upshot of Spinoza allowing for this second, relative
type of common notion is that our ability to transcend mere sense
experience and enter the realm of intellect is not simply a function
of the invariable ontological make-up of the world, of there being
only so many truly universal on/off properties. We can arguably also
<em>do</em> something to increase the number of common notions that it
is possible for beings like us to have, by altering our
&ldquo;usual&rdquo; environments: the more we can make it the case
that we have something in common with things around us &ndash; and in
part this means, the more diverse <em>we</em> ourselves are (cf. Sharp
2011: 98&ndash;9) &ndash; the broader the epistemic
&ldquo;foundation&rdquo; on which we can rely in reasoning.</p>

<p>
Finally, once again, the fact that no common notion <em>on its
own</em> can be a cause of falsity doesn&rsquo;t mean that we cannot
put common notions, of either kind, to bad use: we can still
&ldquo;join&rdquo; adequate ideas to ideas of more dubious value,
producing more complex <em>inadequate</em> representations (cf.
3.2.2). Hence even if we necessarily adequately conceive of God <em>as
a thinking thing</em>, we still are in danger of joining this adequate
idea to that of a benign or vengeful ruler as the referent of the name
<em>God</em>.</p>

<p>
(On reason, see e.g. Kisner 2011; LeBuffe 2017, Malinowski-Charles
2010; on common notions, Donagan 1988; Primus 2017.)</p>

<h4 id="GeneAbst">3.2.4 Generality and abstraction</h4>

<p>
Spinoza&rsquo;s doctrine of common notions is inseparable from a
larger interpretative puzzle. This puzzle concerns Spinoza&rsquo;s
stance on the validity of <em>general</em> concepts more broadly
&ndash; in particular, of concepts of kinds, such as <em>horse,
animal</em>, or <em>being</em>.</p>

<p>
Certain things are fairly clear. For example, it&rsquo;s clear that in
his ontology, Spinoza is committed to the existence of particulars
alone (that is, roughly, things that cannot exist in many places at
the same time) (see e.g., <em>Short Treatise</em> [=<strong>KV]
</strong>1.6[7], E2p48s). It is also clear that, in his view,
conceptual generality &ndash; and in particular the operation of
<em>abstracting</em> from particulars &ndash; is rife with the
possibility of error. (For example, we can be led to overlook
differences among particulars [TIE &sect;76], or mistake the products
of our own abstraction for &ldquo;real beings&rdquo;, when in fact the
resulting ideas present only mind-dependent &ldquo;beings of
reason&rdquo; [<em>Metaphysical Thoughts</em> [= <strong>CM</strong>]
1.1; TIE &sect;93]). Finally, it&rsquo;s also clear that for Spinoza
ideas of universals and abstractions often have <em>lower</em>
epistemic value than ideas of particulars (e.g. TIE &sect;93).</p>

<p>
These considerations have led some readers to take Spinoza to reject
<em>all</em> general and abstract ideas as inadequate (e.g. Curley
1973; Savan 1958). Such readings have trouble explaining
Spinoza&rsquo;s own reliance on words that seem to refer to general
concepts (words such as &ldquo;mode&rdquo;, &ldquo;idea&rdquo;,
&ldquo;cause&rdquo;, etc.). In particular, many of Spinoza&rsquo;s
moral and socio-political doctrines &ndash; and so the whole
enterprise of the <em>Ethics</em> (see 1.4) &ndash; seem to hinge on
the validity of the general idea of &ldquo;human nature&rdquo;.
Spinoza seems to believe that human beings share an essential nature
-- even if they realize this nature to different degrees -- and hence
also a common good. Here is a representative passage:</p>

<blockquote>
the greatest good of those who seek virtue is to know God,
i.e.&hellip;a good that is common to all men, and can be possessed
equally by all men insofar as they are of the same nature (E4p36d; cf.
E4p35, E4AppIX)
</blockquote>

<p>
One interpretative option here is to conclude that for Spinoza general
and abstract ideas such as &ldquo;human nature&rdquo; have only some
<em>pragmatic</em> value (cf. Carriero 2005). Spinoza clearly
recognizes usefulness as an epistemic good (for example, he describes
Aristotelian ideas of genera and species as handy mnemonic devices
[CM1.1]). On such a reading, it might not be strictly speaking true
that there is a common human nature, an immanent universal
instantiated by each particular human being; nonetheless, for ethical
or political ends it might be useful to speak as if there were such a
nature. But such a reading would presumably have trouble explaining in
what sense Spinoza can also insist that the &ldquo;<em>true</em>
knowledge we have of good and evil&rdquo; &ndash; again, hardly a
minor issue for an <em>Ethics</em> &ndash; is &ldquo;abstract,
<em>or</em> universal&rdquo; (E4p62s; G/II/257, emphasis added).</p>

<p>
In solving the puzzle, it helps to be more precise about the nature of
Spinoza&rsquo;s criticisms of general and abstract ideas. First of
all, we should keep in mind the general point that falling short of an
epistemic <em>ideal</em> is not the same as error. Likewise,
mind-dependence is not the same as illusion. (Neither Leibniz nor
Kant, for example, would want to say that the idea or form of space is
an error or an illusion.) Second, Spinoza&rsquo;s most extensive
explicit criticisms of &ldquo;universal&rdquo; and
&ldquo;transcendental&rdquo; ideas, in E2p40s2, is not a criticism of
general ideas <em>simpliciter</em>, as is often assumed, but only of
the Aristotelian premise that <em>sense experience</em> allows us to
form ideas of the <em>essences</em> of things (cf. Bennett 1984). In
Spinoza&rsquo;s view, as finite embodied beings whose minds
essentially track what happens to our bodies (2.2.1), we can&rsquo;t
avoid forming general ideas. In the scholium, he offers a
quasi-mechanistic genealogy of such ideas: Causal encounters with
other bodies are inevitable in a plenum, and just as inevitably they
leave impressions (&ldquo;images&rdquo;) on our bodies. However, the
<em>finitude</em> of our bodies allows them to retain only a limited
number of <em>distinct</em> &ldquo;images&rdquo;; over time, these get
overlaid and confused. The ideas that we form by thinking of these
&ldquo;images&rdquo; &ndash; ideas that we then predicate of indefinitely
many entities, such as <em>horse</em>, <em>animal</em>, or
<em>being</em> &ndash; represent <em>distinctly</em> only what the
bodies we happen to come across have <em>in common</em> insofar as
they <em>can affect</em> a certain <em>kind</em> of body (a human
body) in a certain <em>state</em>. They are not ideas of what
is essential, or even intrinsic, to those external bodies considered
in themselves. In short, in sense experience, we inevitably form
general ideas of kinds of things, and even more abstract
&ldquo;transcendental&rdquo; ideas which cut across kinds. But ideas
formed in this way are just as &ldquo;confused&rdquo; and
&ldquo;inadequate&rdquo; as any other imaginative idea (see 3.2.2).
So, contrary to what the Aristotelians held, sense experience
<em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> suffice for us to form true ideas of the
essences of things. Rather it gives rise to unending philosophical
controversies, as each one of us fashions general types according to
what we happen to experience.</p>

<p>
Finally, we also can&rsquo;t forget that, as we know from our
discussion of common notions (3.2.3), Spinoza doesn&rsquo;t think that
<em>all</em> general ideas grounded in sense experience alone result
in <em>confused</em> representations. For common notions are precisely
those necessarily <em>adequate</em> ideas of what is
&ldquo;equally&rdquo; in all things; that is, they are necessarily
adequate ideas of something like immanent (non-Platonic) universals
that we acquire in any experience whatsoever. Further, beyond this
foundational sphere of common notions, Spinoza seems to think of
&ldquo;reason&rdquo; as such as a necessarily adequate way of
&ldquo;form[ing] universal notions&rdquo;:</p>

<blockquote>
it is clear that we <em>perceive many things and form universal
notions</em>: I. <em>from</em> singular things which have been
represented to us through the senses&hellip; II. <em>from</em>
signs&hellip; These two ways of regarding things I shall henceforth
call knowledge of the first kind, opinion or imagination. III.
Finally, <em>from the fact that we have common notions and adequate
ideas of the properties</em> of things&hellip;This I shall call reason
and the second kind of knowledge (E2p40s2; emphases added)
</blockquote>

<p>
In other words, for Spinoza both (confused and inadequate) imagination
and (necessarily adequate) reason are ways of forming <em>general</em>
(or universal) ideas; what distinguishes reason and imagination is in
part the epistemic value of their respective universal notions. The
general ideas that belong to imagination are, as we have seen,
confused and inadequate and can lead us into error (3.2.2). The
general ideas that belong to reason &ndash; in particular, common
notions and their derivatives &ndash; are, like all ideas of reason,
necessarily adequate (3.2.3). The interpretative question that remains
is of the possible <em>ways</em> we might be able to
&ldquo;form&rdquo; further rational general notion, beyond deriving or
deducing them from common notions.</p>

<p>
(See also e.g. Newlands 2015, H&uuml;bner 2016.)</p>

<h4 id="KindCognIIIIntu">3.2.5 Kinds of cognition III: Intuition</h4>

<p>
In contrast to reason, which for all its epistemic virtues, traffics
only in generalities &ndash; in common notions, ideas of properties of
things, and their derivatives &ndash; intuition (<em>scientia
intuitiva</em>) is a cognition of the <em>essences</em> of particular
things. More specifically, intuition &ldquo;proceeds from an adequate
idea of the formal essence of certain attributes of God to the
adequate knowledge of the [NS: formal] essence of things&rdquo;
(E2p40s2). (Given Spinoza&rsquo;s claim that only infinite things can
&ldquo;follow&rdquo; from infinite things (E1p21&ndash;23), it seems
that the &ldquo;formal essences&rdquo; of particular things that
intuition infers from the essences of divine attributes must
themselves be infinite [D. Garrett 2018:ch.7]. That essences are
<em>unique</em> to the particular things of which they are essences
seems to be an implication of Spinoza&rsquo;s definition of essence in
E2def2.)</p>

<p>
As an intellectual cognition (3.2.3), intuition, like reason, is
&ldquo;necessarily true&rdquo; (E2p41); allows us to
&ldquo;distinguish the true from the false&rdquo; (E2p42); and is
&ldquo;the same in all men&rdquo; (E2p18s). Yet intuition also clearly
<em>exceeds</em> reason as an epistemic achievement in Spinoza&rsquo;s
eyes: it is intuition and not reason that he describes as &ldquo;the
greatest virtue of the mind&rdquo; (E5p25) and the &ldquo;greatest
human perfection&rdquo; (E5p27d), capable of affecting the mind with a
unique degree of force (E5p36s). Intuition is also the only cognition
on which Spinoza bestows the traditional honorific of
&ldquo;<em>scientia</em>&rdquo; (D. Garrett 2018:ch.7).</p>

<p>
What is responsible for this singular place of intuition? Commentators
are divided. Some (e.g. Soyarslan 2016) propose that it allows us to
know truths that reason doesn&rsquo;t. Others (e.g. Nadler 2003) think
intuition is superior to reason as an epistemic <em>method</em> alone.
This latter interpretation is a natural way to understand
Spinoza&rsquo;s own mathematical illustration of the fact that
<em>all</em> kinds of cognition, from imagination to intuition, can
achieve the same (correct) result (E2p40s2). Further, as was the case
for many of Spinoza&rsquo;s predecessors, intuition unlike reason
seems to be for him a matter of <em>immediate</em> insight,
accomplished &ldquo;in one glance&rdquo; (E2p40s2). But the principal
superiority of intuition seems to stem straddle content and method: it
seems to stem from the fact that intuitino is in the business of
cognizing <em>essences</em> directly, without the mediation of ideas
of mere properties of things, whether &ldquo;common&rdquo; properties
or other &ldquo;adequate ideas of properties&rdquo;, which form, as we
have seen, the foundations of reason (3.2.3).</p>

<p>
(See also e.g. Carriero 2020, Primus 2017, Wilson 1999: ch.11.)</p>

<h2 id="EterMind">4. Eternity of the mind</h2>

<p>
Spinoza&rsquo;s doctrine of the eternity of the mind, one of last
subjects of the <em>Ethics</em>, has occasioned some of the most
impatient and uncharitable comments on the part of his readers. (Most
famously perhaps, Bennett 1984 describes it as &ldquo;rubbish&rdquo;
leading others to write rubbish.) The cause for this impatience is
Spinoza&rsquo;s declaration that in Part 5 he will discuss &ldquo;the
mind&rsquo;s duration without relation to the body&rdquo; (E5p20s), a
declaration some see as a blatant violation of his commitment to
mind-body identity in Part 2 (E2p7s). But of course an identity of one
thing with another doesn&rsquo;t rule out the possibility of
<em>discussing</em> one but not the other, a procedure in which
Spinoza engages again and again (for example, in introducing the
possibility of ideas of ideas [see 2.3]). Spinoza is moreover quite
explicit that there is no eternity of human minds without a
corresponding eternity of bodies, and, far from contradicting what he
says about mind-body relations in Part 2, the doctrine of the eternity
of the mind in Part 5 arguably illuminates the fuller meaning of those
earlier commitments.</p>

<p>
To recall (2.2.1), in Part 2 Spinoza proposes that the &ldquo;first
thing&rdquo; that constitutes this &ldquo;actual being&rdquo; of a
human mind is an idea of an &ldquo;actually exist[ing]&rdquo; body
(E2p11&ndash;13). But in Part 5 Spinoza clarifies that
&ldquo;actual&rdquo; being and &ldquo;existence&rdquo; can be
understood in two ways: first, in the temporal (or, more precisely,
&ldquo;durational&rdquo;) sense relevant to his claims in Part 2;
second, in an atemporal and purely ontological sense of simply having
being or reality at all:</p>

<blockquote>
We conceive things as actual in two ways: either insofar as we
conceive them to exist in relation to a certain time and place, or
insofar as we conceive them to be contained in God and to follow from
the necessity of the divine nature. But the things we conceive in this
second way as true, <em>or</em> real, we conceive under a species of
eternity (E5p29s)
</blockquote>

<p>
Given these two senses of &ldquo;actuality&rdquo;, Spinoza&rsquo;s
original claim in Part 2 that the &ldquo;actual being&rdquo; of the
human mind is an idea of an &ldquo;actually exist[ing]&rdquo; body can
also be now understood in two ways. First, it can be understood as a
claim about what it takes for a human mind to begin existing in
<em>duration</em>, as we have done in 2.2.1: any human mind starts to
actually exist in the durational sense when the nexus of bodily causes
in nature generates a new body. The infinite intellect, in its
indefatigable omniscience, begins to represent this body and all its
affections. In the second sense of &ldquo;actual existence&rdquo;, a
human mind is still essentially an &ldquo;actually existing&rdquo;
idea of a certain &ldquo;actually existing&rdquo; bit of extension.
But the relevant bit of extension is not a durational body, but its
eternal <em>essence</em> &ndash; a certain eternally possible way that
divine extension can modify itself to take on a certain ratio of
motion and rest i.e., a determinate functional pattern of physical
activity (cf. E2def[8]; G/II/100). In its omniscience, the divine
substance eternally understands itself as being capable of being
modified in these more determinate ways. As Spinoza puts this, ideas
of these eternal bodily essences are eternally
&ldquo;comprehended&rdquo; in substance&rsquo;s &ldquo;infinite
idea&rdquo; of itself (E2p8) and &ldquo;express&rdquo; the
&ldquo;essence of the body under a species of eternity&rdquo;
(E5p23s).</p>

<p>
The eternal idea of the essence of every body is not only eternally a
part of substance&rsquo;s infinite idea of itself, it is also an eternal
&ldquo;part&rdquo; of the relevant finite mind, a &ldquo;part&rdquo;
that can be said to &ldquo;remain&rdquo; (E5p23) even after the
body&rsquo;s demise, when there are no more ideas of bodily affections
to be &ldquo;felt&rdquo;. This then is all there is to human
immortality, in Spinoza&rsquo;s view: the eternal existence of both
the essences of our bodies, and of ideas of those essences. As Nadler
emphasizes (2002), we are very far here from any traditional doctrine
of <em>personal</em> immortality: nothing that does not belong to us
essentially, and nothing that depends on sense experience, such as
memories, persists beyond death.</p>

<p>
Spinoza writes that we always &ldquo;understand&rdquo; and
&ldquo;feel&rdquo; &ldquo;that we are eternal&rdquo; (E5p23s):
presumably this means that we have some joyful &ndash; i.e., empowering
(E3p11d) &ndash; intellectual grasp of our own eternity (even if most often
we join these adequate ideas to inadequate ones [see 3.2.2], for
example to ideas of <em>reward</em> and <em>punishment</em>). Even
more puzzlingly, he also suggests that we can <em>increase</em> the
degree of our own eternity: &ldquo;the more the mind understands
things by the second and third kind of cognition, the greater the part
[<em>maxima pars</em>] of it that remains&rdquo; after the destruction
of the body (E5p38d). This suggestion might seem puzzling if we assume
that the &ldquo;eternal part&rdquo; of my mind is <em>just</em> the
eternal idea of the eternal essence of <em>my</em> own body. For then
there seems to be nothing that would be subject to improvement or
enlargement: my eternal essence just is my eternal essence.</p>

<p>
Arguably, this is not how Spinoza understands the eternal part of the
mind. The idea of the eternal essence of my own body is after all just
the &ldquo;first thing [<em>primum</em>]&rdquo; (cf. E2p11) that
grounds my mind&rsquo;s eternal existence: it is the
<em>foundation</em> of eternal ideas of other things, just as the
durational idea of this body as changed is the foundation of
imaginative ideas of other things. &ldquo;Whatever the mind
understands under a species of eternity, it understands&hellip;from
the fact that it conceives the body&rsquo;s essence under a species of
eternity&rdquo; (E5p29); &ldquo;the Mind is eternal, insofar as it
conceives things under a species of eternity&rdquo; (E5p31s). In other
words, for Spinoza all cognition of eternal truths rests on a
cognition of our own body as an eternal essence. We can thus
understand the idea of enlarging or maximizing the eternal
&ldquo;part&rdquo; of our minds in terms of the number of eternal
truths, intuitive and rational, that we can acquire in the course of
our existence (or, on innatist readings [see 3.1], the number of
eternal truths that we can make into more powerful &ldquo;parts&rdquo;
of our minds). For Spinoza any human mind is essentially, or first and
foremost, an idea of a certain &ldquo;actually existing&rdquo; body,
and so cognition of that body is the foundation of <em>all</em>
cognition whatsoever. But this is equally true whether we are talking
about merely imaginative cognition of the external bodies we bump up
against in duration; or about the intellectual cognition of eternally
existing essences and of the truths that can be thought about
them.</p>

<p>
(On imaginative cognition of the body, see 2.2 and 3.2.2. On eternity
of the mind, see also e.g. Garrett 2018: ch.9. On Spinoza&rsquo;s debt
to medieval Jewish views about mind&rsquo;s eternity, see e.g. Klein
2014, Nadler 2002, Ravven and Goodman 2002.)</p>
